        <td bgcolor="dimgray" colspan="2" ><img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="1">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;04/25/2001&nbsp;:&nbsp; 14:28:01</font>

        
		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=208"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=208')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&TOPIC_ID=4489&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=The+litmus+for+class+balance"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">You know it's sorta ironic/funny.  At the end of it all verant really has no say over class balance.  Man, this just hit me like a ton of bricks.  They claim they know how to "balance" the classes.  I.e. we have what the player-base calls "nerfs" or changes to the game or a class or an item that weakens something for the sake of "balance" which falls under this greater<BR>umbrella they tell us about called "the vision" (they've rarely if ever strengthened something for balance ... at least, not without a soon to follow weakening on someone else).</P><P>At the end of the day, the players really have the say over class balance.  Bear with me here. It's not instant, or quickly noticeable.  Rather, it's gradual, casual but once it arrives it's as undeniable as the nose on your face.  It might take a new expansion to settle in for 6 months.  It might take the discovery, broadly, of a useful item (o'donals bp), but eventually it's here.</P><P>I'm talking about raids, bosses and the desired classes to take 'em on.  If balance were truly in the game then everyone<BR>wouldn't be dumping their necros (or whathaveyou) to make a warrior or a cleric, but they are.  Sure, VI will blame this/that/theotherthing for people deciding to switch classes, but it is plain as anything that people make a warrior because they do better/are in more demand on raids than, say, a necro.  The same goes for a cleric.</P><P>Verant can't force anyone to play any class.  I'm not sure if they've ever nerfed for the sake of making a certain class more desirable (I think warriors were always in abundance even in their suckiest day when any same-lvl-necro pet could wax 'em -- and gee, like rangers have ever been extinct).  The point is, the litmus test for class balance is, in the end, the classes most in demand for raids.</P><P>If classes were truly balances then the uber guilds (the entities that build the best fighting groups EQ can front), would want as many necros as warriors as druids as shaman as clerics.  I could see if it were sorta close, but it's not.  In my guild they were discussing recruitment.  They want casters, casters and more casters.  The comment was made "a few druids is a few druids too many." The same sorta stuff is said about necros.  Do you think such a thing might ever be said about clerics?!?</P><P>The litmus for class balance is demand for guild raids and right now, VI is failing it.</P><P>It's the classes most in demand for raids that truly decides if things are really balanced, and right now they are not.  Right now, you wouldn't trade an extra cleric for an extra necro.  You wouldn't dare go into a raid without the allotted number of tanks, but dang if anyone can put a figure on the needed number of necros in a raid.  What is it.  1?</P><P>I am of the elves that hated the light and returned unto the darkness.</font></td>
      </tr>

